}
```

**Asymptotic Notations: Big-O, Big-Omega, Big-Theta with examples**

Big O notation represents the upper bound of an algorithm's time complexity. It measures how long an algorithm takes as input size increases.

Example:
Suppose we have an algorithm that prints all prime numbers up to a given number n.
The time complexity is O(n), because the algorithm needs to check each number from 2 to n (inclusive) for primality.

Big-Omega notation represents the lower bound of an algorithm's time complexity. It measures how long an algorithm takes as input size increases, but it is always greater than or equal to the actual running time.

Example:
Suppose we have an algorithm that prints all prime numbers up to a given number n.
The time complexity is Ω(n), because the algorithm needs to check each number from 2 to n (inclusive) for primality.

Big-Theta notation represents the exact time complexity of an algorithm. It measures how long an algorithm takes as input size increases, and it is equal to the actual running time.

Example:
Suppose we have an algorithm that prints all prime numbers up to a given number n.
The time complexity is Θ(n), because the algorithm needs to check each number from 2 to n (inclusive) for primality.

